{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Key Insight: Associativity of Matrix Multiplication"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Standard attention computes "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "softmax(QKᵀ/√d)·V"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The bottleneck is the T×T matrix "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "QKᵀ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — it must be materialised in memory before the softmax can be applied. Linear attention sidesteps this by replacing the softmax with a kernel function φ(·) and exploiting matrix multiplication's associativity:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{Attn}(Q,K,V)_i = \\frac{\\phi(q_i)^\\top (\\sum_j \\phi(k_j) v_j^\\top)}{\\phi(q_i)^\\top (\\sum_j \\phi(k_j))}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The inner sum "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "S = Σⱼ φ(kⱼ)vⱼᵀ ∈ ℝ^{d×d}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " can be accumulated once and reused for all queries. Training cost drops from O(T²d) to O(Td²). The T×T matrix is never formed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Softmax attention requires materialising T×T score matrix; linear attention accumulates a d×d state S that replaces the T×T matrix"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Kernel Function φ"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For linear attention to approximate softmax attention, φ must satisfy "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "φ(q)ᵀφ(k) ≈ exp(qᵀk)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The random Fourier features (RFF) approach uses random projections to approximate the RBF kernel. In practice most implementations use simpler choices that are fast and non-negative (ensuring the normaliser "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "φ(q)ᵀΣφ(k)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " stays positive):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "φ(x) = elu(x) + 1"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — used in the original Linear Transformer paper (Katharopoulos et al., 2020). Simple, non-negative."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "φ(x) = relu(x)²"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — used in several efficient transformer variants. Encourages sparsity in attention patterns."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "φ(x) = [sin(ωx); cos(ωx)]"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — random Fourier features, theoretically principled but higher-dimensional and slower."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\nclass LinearAttention(nn.Module):\n    \"\"\"Causal linear attention via cumulative outer-product state.\"\"\"\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, n_heads: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.n_heads = n_heads\n        self.d_k = d_model // n_heads\n        self.W_q = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_k = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_v = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_o = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n\n    @staticmethod\n    def kernel(x):\n        \"\"\"φ(x) = elu(x) + 1 — non-negative, fast.\"\"\"\n        return F.elu(x) + 1\n\n    def forward(self, x):\n        B, T, _ = x.shape\n        H, d_k = self.n_heads, self.d_k\n\n        q = self.kernel(self.W_q(x)).view(B, T, H, d_k).transpose(1, 2)  # (B,H,T,d_k)\n        k = self.kernel(self.W_k(x)).view(B, T, H, d_k).transpose(1, 2)\n        v =              self.W_v(x) .view(B, T, H, d_k).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        # Causal: accumulate S = Σ_{j≤t} φ(k_j) v_j^T step by step\n        # S: (B, H, d_k, d_k) — the d_k × d_k \"context state\"\n        # z: (B, H, d_k)       — normaliser Σ_{j≤t} φ(k_j)\n        outputs = []\n        S = torch.zeros(B, H, d_k, d_k, device=x.device)\n        z = torch.zeros(B, H, d_k,      device=x.device)\n\n        for t in range(T):\n            kt = k[:, :, t, :]   # (B, H, d_k)\n            vt = v[:, :, t, :]   # (B, H, d_k)\n            qt = q[:, :, t, :]   # (B, H, d_k)\n\n            S = S + kt.unsqueeze(-1) * vt.unsqueeze(-2)  # outer product update\n            z = z + kt\n\n            # Output for position t: φ(q_t)ᵀ S / (φ(q_t)ᵀ z)\n            num = (qt.unsqueeze(-2) @ S).squeeze(-2)     # (B, H, d_k)\n            den = (qt * z).sum(dim=-1, keepdim=True) + 1e-6\n            outputs.append(num / den)\n\n        out = torch.stack(outputs, dim=2)   # (B, H, T, d_k)\n        out = out.transpose(1, 2).reshape(B, T, H * d_k)\n        return self.W_o(out)\n\n# The loop above is O(T·d²) total — no T×T matrix ever created\nmodel = LinearAttention(d_model=128, n_heads=4)\nx = torch.randn(2, 64, 128)\nout = model(x)\nprint(out.shape)   # (2, 64, 128)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Recurrent Form and O(1) Inference"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The cumulative state "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "S"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has a natural recurrent update rule:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "S_t = S_{t-1} + \\phi(k_t) v_t^\\top, \\quad o_t = \\frac{\\phi(q_t)^\\top S_t}{\\phi(q_t)^\\top z_t}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At inference time, this is exactly an RNN with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "d×d"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " matrix hidden state. Each new token costs O(d²) to process — constant regardless of how many tokens have been generated. The KV cache disappears entirely, replaced by a fixed-size state. This is the same inference-time efficiency as an LSTM, with the parallelisable training of a transformer."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Quality Trade-off"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The softmax's normalisation makes it a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "data-dependent"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " selector: a single past token can receive nearly all attention weight. The linear kernel's normaliser "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "φ(q)ᵀΣφ(k)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is much smoother, so attention is spread more diffusely. On tasks that require precise, focused retrieval (named entity recognition, subject-verb agreement at distance), linear attention loses 1–3 perplexity points versus softmax."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Models like RetNet and GLA (Gated Linear Attention) add decay gates to the state update — "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Sₜ = γ·Sₜ₋₁ + φ(kₜ)vₜᵀ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " — that let the model forget irrelevant context. This closes much of the quality gap at the cost of a single element-wise multiply per step."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\ndef gated_linear_attn_step(qt, kt, vt, S, z, gamma=0.99):\n    \"\"\"\n    One step of Gated Linear Attention.\n    gamma: per-step decay — forgets older context exponentially.\n    qt, kt, vt: (d_k,) vectors for current token\n    S: (d_k, d_k) state matrix\n    z: (d_k,) normaliser\n    \"\"\"\n    # Decay old state then add new key-value outer product\n    S = gamma * S + kt.unsqueeze(-1) * vt.unsqueeze(-2)\n    z = gamma * z + kt\n    num = qt @ S          # (d_k,)\n    den = qt @ z + 1e-6   # scalar\n    return S, z, num / den\n\nd_k = 64\nS = torch.zeros(d_k, d_k)\nz = torch.zeros(d_k)\noutputs = []\n\ntorch.manual_seed(0)\nfor _ in range(100):   # 100 tokens\n    q = torch.relu(torch.randn(d_k)) + 1\n    k = torch.relu(torch.randn(d_k)) + 1\n    v = torch.randn(d_k)\n    S, z, o = gated_linear_attn_step(q, k, v, S, z)\n    outputs.append(o)\n\nprint(torch.stack(outputs).shape)  # (100, 64)\n# State S is always (d_k, d_k) = 64×64 — never grows with sequence length"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "The unifying view: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Linear attention is essentially an RNN whose hidden state is a d×d matrix instead of a d-vector, updated by outer products of key and value. The kernel function φ plays the role of a non-linear activation. This connects attention back to the recurrent models it replaced — and explains why the next generation of architectures (Mamba, RWKV, GLA, RetNet) are sometimes called \"linear recurrent models\" or \"state space models\": they are all instances of this outer-product state update with different gating mechanisms."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
